Conn syndrome was named after J. W. Conn who first described it in 1955, in a patient who had hypertension with an aldosterone-producing adenoma.

[!INFO] Features of Conn's syndrome:

  • Elevated Na
  • Hypokalemia
  • Metabolic alkalosis
  • Impaired glucose tolerance (hypokalemia inhibits insulin secretion)
  • Source
Diagnosis of Conn's syndrome
  • Graves ophthalmolathy [[#^4c27cc|See below]] is a prominent feature. Occurs because of T cell infiltrations;

[!INFO] Definition of Graves ophthalmopathy:
Ophthalmopathy is characterized by inflammation of the extraocular muscles and orbital fat and connective tissue, which results in proptosis (exophthalmos), impairment of eye muscle function, and periorbital edema.

(In a child with thyrotoxicosis) the presence of eye findings such as exophthalmos or ocular muscle dysfunction essentially always points to Graves disease. "Stare" and lid lag are common in children with any form of hyperthyroidism and occur due to increased sympathetic tone.

Volume of retro-orbital tissue is increased by 1) T cell infiltration, 2) Inflammatory oedema, 3) Increased extracellular matrix deposition, 4) increased adipocytes.
Graves dermopathy and ophthalmopathy may also be due to TRAb antibody reactivity with eye and skin tissue which may also express TSH receptor like protein. - UpToDate.

^4c27cc

[!INFO] Eye signs
Lid retraction: can be of the upper or lower eye lid. Definitions are varied and confusing.
Lid lag: Failure of the upper eye lid follow the globe as the gaze is moved donwards.
Source
As above, lid retraction is more suggestive of Grave's ophthalmopathy.

Definition of conjugated hyperbilirubinemia

#2021SBR-NOV

[!INFO] Definition of direct / conjugated hyperbilirubinemia
Direct bilirubin > 2 mg/dL or more than 20% of Total Serum Bilirubin.

[!INFO] Effect on C peptide
#2021SBR-NOV Q05
Since sulfonylureas stimulate the release of endogenous insulin, the plasma levels of insulin and C-peptide are inappropriately high in patients with sulfonylurea-induced hypoglycemia. These plasma levels are higher than those in patients with an insulinoma. Source

Autoimmune hepatitis

75% female predominance.
Strongly associated with either personal or family history of autoimmune disease.

  • Perimenopausal ladies will present with mild fatigue and elevated liver enzymes.
  • Girls in teens and early twenties will present with acute hepatitis with very high liver enzymes.

1/3 of patients have cirrhocis at presentation!.

Treatment: Initiated with steroid and azathioprine. Lifelong treatment usually required.
The good news is that 80% go into remission with treatment. FC

Other features of autoimmune disease may be present in the young group:

  • Fever,
  • Migratory polyarthritis
  • Glomerulonpheritis
  • Pulmonary infiltration or lung fibrosis

Investigations: AST, ALT high. ALP moderately high. High gamma globulins, elevated PT.
Biopsy is mandatory to confirm the dianosis; It will show interface hepatitis and chronic active hepatitis.
Type I AIH has ANA and anti-smooth muscle antibodies.
Type II - anti liver kidney microsomal antibodies. LKM1

C peptide

The 2 major indications for measuring C-peptide levels include fasting hypoglycemia and assessment of insulin secretory reserve in patients with diabetes.

  • C peptide half life is about 30 minutes. Source
  • C-peptide is secreted in equimolar concentrations with insulin from the beta cells.
  • It is a valid measure of insulin secretion especially following challenges with glucagon or a mixed meal.
  • C-peptide is extremely useful in the differential diagnosis of hyperinsulinemic-hypoglycemia.
  • [[General medicine 5#Sulfonylureas|C peptide level is increased by sulfonylureas]]

Coeliac disease

Gluten sensitive enteropathy (GSE)
One of the diseases causing intestinal malabsorption

[!TIP] Diseases causing intestinal malabsorption
Cats dance better than iguanas wearing red pants

Pathogenesis

  • Gluten is the protein content found in cereals.
  • Prolamins are proteins which have high glutamine and proline content so they don't get digested by pepsin and pass into the intestine.
  • Prolamins actually pass through the epithelium and undergo deamination by transglutaminase which makes them more immunogenic.
  • CD4 T cells are stimulated and the resulting inflammation causes disease.
  • Interferon gamma is involved.
  • The disease process results in crypt hyperplasia and villous atrophy.

#2021GM-NOV Q31

Medullary thyroid Cancer (MTC)

  • Progressive and chronic liver disease caused by autoimmune mediated fibrosis of intra and extrahepatic bile ducts.
  • Strongly associated with IBD (mainly ulcerative colitis)
  • Associated with pANCA positivity.
  • Often complicated by recurrent cholangitis and cholangiocarcinoma.
  • Treament is not curative; it's aimed at minimizing symptoms and managing complications.
  • Liver transplantation is the only treatment than can alter progression. Drugs won't work.
  • Affects young to middle aged males (in their 40s)
    • PSC without IBD is more likely to occur in women.
    • PSC is seen predominantly in non smokers.
    • (Remember that smoking protects against ulcerative colitis! so if you smoke, you have less risk of UC and associated PSC)
  • Ix: AST, ALT, GGT all elevated. Fluctuating conjugated hyperbilirubinaemia.
  • hypergammaglobulinaemia is present.
  • Best imaging modality: MRCP
  • ultimately leads to cirrhocis.

Primary Biliary Cirrhocis / Primary Biliary Cholangitis

[!TIP] PBC - the C can stant for Cirrhocis or Cholangitis.

[!TIP] When to suspect
Suspect in a middle aged woman with pruritus who has elevated ALP and possible other autoimmune conditions.

MCQ Discussion:
Most often diagnosed through routine screening. Usually asymptomatic.
But Fatigue is a prominent presenting symptom. Icterus and pruritus are late signs.

  • 95% of PBC occurs in women aged 40 - 50 years.
  • There is destruction of small interlobular bile ducts.
  • Antimitochondrial antibodies are found in all patients. M2 is specific for PBC.
  • Presentation: Asymptomatic with #hepatomegaly and raised ALP. (raised ALP is often the only abnormal investigation)
  • Pruritus and fatigue.
  • Raised cholesterol and Xanthelasma
  • Associated with many autoimmune conditions.
  • Histology: portal tract infiltrate with hepatic granulomas; changes start in zone 1.
